collections.name: A futuristic digital artwork depicting the clash b
Decohering Delineation
collections.description: A bird calls, a fish surfaces, a dandelion sheds its seeds in a gust of air. However, when events stretch out across hours, days and more, we no longer readily perceive, but rely on the labelling of such events as abstract groupings we “know” to be, yet have no visible delineation. 'Decohering Delineation' is the entanglement of neural networks and oceanic data as an experimental exploration of ways to make tangible, through the use of quantum computation and neural networks, the innate interconnected nature of ecosystems and specimens, artificial & natural. Neural networks normally cannot reproduce patterns outside of the data used to train them, but through the use of quantum circuits and marine data, the shifting regions of entanglement create spaces of external--internal influence, allowing patterns of Others to exist within them.

collections.name: self-contained
collections.description: This piece, part of the 'self-contained' series, draws inspiration from the mechanisms of encoding and decoding information in DNA, applying these principles to the process of image-making. By integrating evolutionary dynamics, including crossbreeding and random mutations, the work echoes the memetic characteristics of digital spaces, where images are constantly merged, altered, degraded, or recontextualized. Departing from more conventional methods, a target image is iteratively crossbred with random segments of other compressed images. This creates a mutative evolution, akin to grafting plants, where the visual “genome” is spliced with data from the broader dataset. Additionally, simple artificial life (a-life) simulations are utilised to explore 'error correction' during this mutative process, tentatively mapping the complexity of natural systems. The decoding stage reconstructs the image into a more recognisable form, supported by neural networks trained on the same dataset to restore colour and detail. This work portrays the ongoing, concurrent cycle of compression and decompression, a phenomenon mirrored in the constant evolution of shared digital spaces. Just as our cells divide, mutate, and evolve, the content in these spaces is remixed, reshaped, and, eventually, replaced. With 'self-contained 009.x,' an additional layer of self-containment is achieved: a compressed version of the final work is synthesised and stored in DNA, enclosed within a custom-made sculptural container. This brings the work full circle, from simulated natural processes in image-making to the ultimate re-encoding of the digital into physical, synthesised DNA.

collections.name: The Banquet
collections.description:
The Banquet

An original 110x160 cm oil painting, once showcased in Lisbon and now in Switzerland, explores the duality of human existence. At its center, Pope Francis embodies the tension between spiritual anguish and rampant greed, with the “Cross of the Pope” portraying Christ guiding a fragmented world under divine protection. Themes of the Holocaust, the American Dream’s collapse, and China’s rise weave through the composition, punctuated by the haunting image of a war-torn child.

Inspired by Tarot card 18 (The Moon), a scarlet lobster symbolizes emotional turbulence beneath a stormy sky, where hope and despair collide. Symbols like a green handkerchief honor Portugal’s resilience, while a virus looms ominously alongside the promise of a vaccine. A crow, cat, and blindfolded woman personify death, wisdom, and uncertainty, while Pinocchio’s presence critiques humanity’s prejudices.

Ascending figures at the top inspire unity and courage, offering a vision of renewal amidst chaos.

Briyan is best known as the publisher of **[GAJOOB Zine](https://gajoobzine.com)** and a founder of the **[Tapegerm Collective](https://tapegerm.com)**. You'll find his music on **[GAJOOB Records & Tapes](https://gajoob.bandcamp.com)**.

collections.name: ABSTRACT ART AT 80
collections.description:
This collection, Abstract Art at 80, represents the vision of abstract art from an 80-year-old grandfather, with no previous experience in painting. The basis of my works are multiple images made manually, using the technique of rectillism, which I later combine, in a novel and irreverent way, with the help of a computer. It is computational craftsmanship, very eye-catching and original. The use of artificial intelligence in all its forms, art machines, and other similar tools, are completely excluded. The result is abstract works, of medium size upwards and possible to edit in various configurations, which makes them very versatile. To date, they add up to a large number, all different and have never been exposed to third parties by any means. They will appear in Open Sea progressively. I invite you to see this first collection, Abstract Art at 80, it will be a pleasant experience. 

I also invite you to check out my portfolio:

https://drive.google.com/file/d/11clxYjnuJ0T7agsScHbluAL

collections.name: ROSES
collections.description: Dilorom's unique technique can be traced back to Oshibana art. The artist collects and dries the petals of wild roses to create paintings using pressed petals, a scalpel and glue. She works with natural plant colours instead of conventional paints. Dilorom avoids any oil or pastels and chooses carefully shades for every detail of the work: eyes, hair, eyebrows, and eyelashes. As a result, natural velvet colors are preserved to give a great depth to the colour scheme of the paintings. When working on portraits, she strives to make the surface feel smooth and avoid patchiness.
